=== Projective schemes ===
For various applications, it is necessary to consider more general algebro-geometric objects than projective varieties, namely projective schemes. The first step towards projective schemes is to endow projective space with a scheme structure, in a way refining the above description of projective space as an algebraic variety, i.e., formula_37 is a scheme which it is a union of (&quot;n&quot; + 1) copies of the affine &quot;n&quot;-space &quot;kn&quot;. More generally, projective space over a ring &quot;A&quot; is the union of the affine schemes

:formula_38

in such a way the variables match up as expected. The set of closed points of formula_39, for algebraically closed fields &quot;k&quot;, is then the projective space formula_37 in the usual sense.

An equivalent but streamlined construction is given by the Proj construction, which is an analog of the spectrum of a ring, denoted &quot;Spec&quot;, which defines an affine scheme. For example, if &quot;A&quot; is a ring, then

:formula_41

If &quot;R&quot; is a quotient of formula_42 by a homogeneous ideal &quot;I&quot;, then the canonical surjection induces the closed immersion

:formula_43

Compared to projective varieties, the condition that the ideal &quot;I&quot; be a prime ideal was dropped. This leads to a much more flexible notion: on the one hand the topological space formula_44 may have multiple irreducible components. Moreover, there may be nilpotent functions on &quot;X&quot;.

Closed subschemes of formula_39 correspond bijectively to the homogeneous ideals &quot;I&quot; of formula_42 that are saturated; i.e., formula_47 This fact may be considered as a refined version of projective Nullstellensatz.

